      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\vr(t) = \langle \sin(5t), \sin(4t) \rangle</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            This function is called a Lissajous, or Bowditch, curve.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            This function is called a Lissajous, or Bowditch, curve.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\vr(t) = \langle t^2\sin(t)\cos(t), 0.9t\cos(t^2), \sin(t) \rangle</m>. (Note that this defines a curve in three-dimensional space.)
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            For <m>0 \leq t \leq \pi</m>, the function has <m>z</m>-values between 0 and 1. For <m>\pi \leq t \leq 2 \pi</m>, the function has <m>z</m>-values between -1 and 0. The function snakes its way outwards and then goes back to zero. It behaves similarly in the <m>y</m>-direction.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            For <m>0 \leq t \leq \pi</m>, the function has <m>z</m>-values between 0 and 1. For <m>\pi \leq t \leq 2 \pi</m>, the function has <m>z</m>-values between -1 and 0. The function snakes its way outwards and then goes back to zero. It behaves similarly in the <m>y</m>-direction.
